rvice users in adapting to the extraordinary pressures of the pandemic on policy, practice and lived experience. The text integrates first-hand narrative and artistic accounts from a variety of key stakeholders experiencing the Criminal Justice System (CJS). The editors recommend a range of evidence-based policy and practice improvements, not only in terms of planning for future pandemics, but also those that will benefit the CJS and its stakeholders in the longer term.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCOVID-19 Pandemic, 2020-xSocial aspectszEngland. 0aCOVID-19 Pandemic, 2020-xSocial aspectszWales. 0aCriminal justice, Administration ofxHistoryy21st centuryzEngland. 0aCriminal justice, Administration ofxHistoryy21st centuryzWales. 0aCriminal justice, Administration ofzEnglandxHistoryy21st century. 0aCriminal justice, Administration ofzWalesxHistoryy21st century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Criminology.2bisacsh1 aAinslie, Sam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Tom, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarnighan, Maureen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCase, Stephen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCase, Stephen, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCoxhead, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aForder, Phil, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFowler, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFowler, Rachel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHaines, Abbie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHamilton, Ian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb